for going into work

26:10.007 --> 26:12.843
instead of staying home.
- No.

26:12.878 --> 26:16.044
No, she's really good.

26:16.079 --> 26:17.914
Does Claudio know?

26:17.949 --> 26:19.278
- Not yet.

26:19.313 --> 26:20.653
He's left messages.

26:20.688 --> 26:22.545
- You should let him know.

26:22.580 --> 26:26.483
At least that she might not
be able to get back on the road.

26:26.518 --> 26:30.256
Give him a chance to cancel
the dates or find a replacement.

26:30.291 --> 26:33.292
- I just worry
that without the tour,

26:33.327 --> 26:37.428
she won't have
anything to live for.

26:37.463 --> 26:40.266
- But we already know
it wasn't enough, right?

27:04.765 --> 27:07.931
- What are you reading?

27:07.966 --> 27:11.594
- My novel.

27:11.629 --> 27:15.103
- Another radio story?

27:15.138 --> 27:16.841
- No, this is
the "book" book.

27:16.876 --> 27:18.304
The real book.

27:18.339 --> 27:20.141
Did you know that Mom
played the word "vulva"

27:20.176 --> 27:21.538
at the Scrabble club
the other day?

27:21.573 --> 27:23.078
- Is it done?

27:23.113 --> 27:24.750
- She said that the guy
she was playing with,

27:24.785 --> 27:26.950
who was much younger, couldn't
look her in the eye after.

27:26.985 --> 27:28.182
- Is it finished?

27:28.217 --> 27:31.218
I don't want to talk about it.

27:31.253 --> 27:34.760
- Hmm.
Well, it looks finished.

27:34.795 --> 27:35.827
You want to read me
a little bit?

27:35.862 --> 27:37.521
- No.

27:37.556 --> 27:39.358
- Come on, swift.

27:39.393 --> 27:40.898
Read me a page!

27:40.933 --> 27:42.867
- No.
- Okay, a paragraph?

27:42.902 --> 27:44.561
- No.
- A sentence?

27:44.596 --> 27:45.804
- No!
- Word?

27:45.839 --> 27:47.036
- Okay.
Alright.

27:47.071 --> 27:50.006
I will read you the first
letter of my novel.

27:51.570 --> 27:54.670
Yeah.

27:54.705 --> 27:55.572
- Okay.

27:57.411 --> 27:59.015
"L."

28:02.350 --> 28:04.350
- Mmm...
it's brilliant.

28:07.256 --> 28:09.157
I think it might be the best
thing you've ever written.

28:09.192 --> 28:10.653
- Really?
- Really.

28:10.688 --> 28:12.127
- Thank you so much!

28:12.162 --> 28:14.261
That means so much to me.

28:18.729 --> 28:20.564
- What's your book about?

28:40.751 --> 28:45.325
♪

28:45.360 --> 28:50.297
♪

28:50.332 --> 28:54.466
♪

28:54.501 --> 28:59.108
♪

28:59.143 --> 29:02.672
♪

29:02.707 --> 29:05.884
- I'm gonna
go get a coffee.

29:11.023 --> 29:13.617
YOLI V.O.: Continents
drift apart at the same rate

29:13.652 --> 29:16.686
as fingernails grow.

29:16.721 --> 29:20.525
♪

29:20.560 --> 29:24.397
Or is it the other way around?

29:24.432 --> 29:28.137
I forget.

29:28.172 --> 29:31.800
♪

29:31.835 --> 29:34.440
♪

29:45.684 --> 29:47.486
- What's in the bag?

29:47.521 --> 29:49.521
- My novel.

29:52.361 --> 29:54.999
- Elf says
the first letter is great,

29:55.034 --> 29:57.969
but that you're being very
secretive about other details.

29:58.004 --> 30:01.401
- It's I...
I just didn't...

30:01.436 --> 30:05.009
I just didn't feel like
talking about it with her.

30:05.044 --> 30:06.978
- How many
words do you have?

30:07.013 --> 30:09.343
- I haven't counted.
- And will it be sad?

30:09.378 --> 30:11.180
Because there hasn't
been a book of yours

30:11.215 --> 30:15.712
that I finished reading
and haven't felt like crying.

30:15.747 --> 30:19.892
You carry a lot of sadness,
and for that I am sorry.

30:26.428 --> 30:28.934
YOLI V.O.: I wanted to tell
my mother that when I was a kid,

30:28.969 --> 30:31.970
I woke up every morning singing,

30:32.005 --> 30:35.732
that there was no freer soul
in the world than me at six.

30:35.767 --> 30:38.603
♪

30:38.638 --> 30:41.980
- You are not to blame.

30:42.015 --> 30:43.839
I'm not like her.

30:43.874 --> 30:45.742
I'm not like Dad.

30:49.088 --> 30:50.714
- No, me neither.

30:57.261 --> 31:00.196
- Oh, shit.

31:06.897 --> 31:10.404
- It appears
as though the car is dead.

31:10.439 --> 31:12.868
- Oh, boy.

31:12.903 --> 31:16.509
The metaphors seem to be
popping up all over the place!

31:16.544 --> 31:18.874
- Mom!
- Sorry.

31:18.909 --> 31:20.711
- Ah, thank God
the rest of our lives

31:20.746 --> 31:22.284
are going so well,
otherwise...

31:22.319 --> 31:23.648
I don't know how we'd cope.

31:23.683 --> 31:25.452
- So...?

31:27.423 --> 31:28.851
- Uh--

31:28.886 --> 31:30.589
Well, we're not
that far from home.

31:30.624 --> 31:32.195
Should we walk?

31:32.230 --> 31:34.890
- Yeah.
Yeah, I need the exercise.

31:34.925 --> 31:39.301
And I haven't had a bowel
movement in three days.

31:52.910 --> 31:54.382
- Where have you been?

31:54.417 --> 31:55.911
I've been trying to get in touch
with you since yesterday.

31:55.946 --> 31:58.386
- Yeah.
Look, there's some sort of...

31:58.421 --> 32:00.586
I don't know, like,
accountant-looking guy who says

32:00.621 --> 32:02.357
that you sent him
here to check on me?

32:02.392 --> 32:03.919
- That's Finbar.
He's actually a lawyer.

32:03.954 --> 32:05.162
Yes, I did.

32:05.197 --> 32:06.757
- Who is he?

32:06.792 --> 32:08.957
- Well, why haven't you
been answering your phone?

32:08.992 --> 32:10.563
- I lost it.
Look, please don't tell me

32:10.598 --> 32:11.729
you're dating this guy.

32:11.764 --> 32:13.104
- How did you
lose your phone?

32:13.139 --> 32:14.699
- I don't know.
I keep hoping it'll reappear.

32:14.734 --> 32:17.075
So you're dating him?
- No, we're friends.

32:17.110 --> 32:19.209
Will you pass him
the phone for me?

32:19.244 --> 32:21.409
- He seems creepy.

32:21.444 --> 32:22.839
- Pass him the phone.

32:35.018 --> 32:37.491
- Congratulations on
your upgrade to the psych ward.

32:43.961 --> 32:45.697
- Tell me something, Elf.

32:45.732 --> 32:47.336
Anything.

32:53.036 --> 32:55.146
- You still seeing
that violin player?

32:55.181 --> 32:57.445
- No.

32:57.480 --> 32:59.381
Kind of.

32:59.416 --> 33:02.417
- What about that lawyer?
What's his name, Alex?

33:02.452 --> 33:05.288
- Finbar.

33:05.323 --> 33:07.686
- Finbar...

33:07.721 --> 33:09.292
- Are you dating?

33:09.327 --> 33:11.019
- Oh, I don't know
what it is...

33:11.054 --> 33:14.165
or how to define it.

33:14.200 --> 33:16.332
Ending 16 years
of monogamy with Dan

33:16.367 --> 33:18.631
has triggered some kind of...

33:18.666 --> 33:22.206
I don't know, like,
weird animal reaction.

33:24.034 --> 33:25.737
To be honest,
the past few months

33:25.772 --> 33:28.212
have not been my proudest.

33:28.247 --> 33:31.908
I might be a slut now.

33:31.943 --> 33:34.548
- Are you using protection?

33:34.583 --> 33:37.518
- Would that
make a difference?

33:37.553 --> 33:39.553
If I got pregnant, would...

33:39.588 --> 33:42.061
would that give you something
to look forward to?

33:50.764 --> 33:52.665
What are we doing here, Elf?

33:52.700 --> 33:55.470
- Talking.
- You know what I mean.

33:58.035 --> 34:00.079
Do you have any desire
to rejoin the world?

34:07.154 --> 34:09.682
And are you thinking at all
of the reasons to stay alive?

34:18.957 --> 34:20.297
How was your visit
with Nic last night?

34:20.332 --> 34:21.562
How's he doing?

34:21.597 --> 34:22.695
- Stop it.

34:22.730 --> 34:24.136
- It must
be terrible for him.

34:24.171 --> 34:25.764
- Stop!
- Have you, um,

34:25.799 --> 34:28.272
showered, eaten breakfast,
checked your phone,

34:28.307 --> 34:30.032
taken your meds,
talked to your psychiatrist?

34:30.067 --> 34:32.111
- Don't interrogate me.

34:48.558 --> 34:52.395
♪

34:52.430 --> 34:54.595
♪

34:54.630 --> 34:57.796
- The other day,
I was walking down this alley

34:57.831 --> 35:00.766
and there was an old man

35:00.801 --> 35:03.604
trying to erase

35:03.639 --> 35:06.772
some graffiti from
the top of this wall.

35:06.807 --> 35:08.609
He was standing
on a really low stool,

35:08.644 --> 35:10.072
like a foot off the ground,
tops,

35:10.107 --> 35:12.745
and his wife was
holding on to his hips

35:12.780 --> 35:16.353
so he wouldn't fall.

35:16.388 --> 35:18.322
And they were so old

35:18.357 --> 35:22.150
and so concerned for each other
it made me want to cry.

35:22.185 --> 35:25.428
♪

35:25.463 --> 35:28.431
- Have you embedded some
type of parable into this story,

35:28.466 --> 35:30.664
something you'll
hope I'll take away?

35:30.699 --> 35:32.765
- You mean like
something about not giving up?

35:32.800 --> 35:34.833
- Yeah.
- No.

35:34.868 --> 35:36.769
In fact, the lesson
one could take away

35:36.804 --> 35:38.276
from this particular anecdote

35:38.311 --> 35:40.806
is to stop risking your life
to maintain a clean wall.

35:49.850 --> 35:53.357
- Will you take me
to Switzerland?

35:53.392 --> 35:55.359
- Yes.

35:55.394 --> 35:58.791
Yeah, we could get Swatches.

35:58.826 --> 36:01.057
- Is that what you think of
when you think of Switzerland?

36:01.092 --> 36:02.828
- Mm-hm.
That and yodelling.

36:02.863 --> 36:04.533
And perfectly
organized closets.

36:04.568 --> 36:06.733
It feels like there's nothing
out of place in that country.

36:06.768 --> 36:10.737
- They have clinics there
where dying is legal,

36:10.772 --> 36:13.036
where you don't
have to die alone.

36:16.976 --> 36:18.844
- Why are these here?

36:23.917 --> 36:26.456
- I was having coffee
with a young mother.

36:26.491 --> 36:29.217
She's going through a rough
patch and she asked me

36:29.252 --> 36:31.857
if I would keep them so she
wouldn't be tempted to fire them

36:31.892 --> 36:33.496
into her head.

36:33.531 --> 36:37.060
- How could she fire
two bullets into her own head?

36:37.095 --> 36:39.502
- The other one
was for her daughter

36:39.537 --> 36:43.671
so she wouldn't be
leaving her alone.

36:43.706 --> 36:46.839
- No.

36:46.874 --> 36:49.809
No, Elf, I will not
take you to Switzerland.

36:49.844 --> 36:51.514
- I'm asking you
to do this for me, Yoli.

36:51.549 --> 36:53.175
- No.

36:53.210 --> 36:54.550
- I have a terminal illness.

36:54.585 --> 36:57.113
- You don't.
You don't.

36:57.148 --> 36:59.885
No, you're asking me to take
you to Switzerland to be killed.

36:59.920 --> 37:02.624
Are you out of
your fucking mind?

37:10.469 --> 37:12.535
Do you have any idea
how much I would miss you?

37:42.468 --> 37:46.701
You're not a slut.

37:46.736 --> 37:48.505
Didn't I teach you anything?

38:07.658 --> 38:10.692
- You're Elf's
psychiatrist, right?

38:10.727 --> 38:13.090
DR.- Who?

38:13.125 --> 38:15.961
- Elfrieda Von Riesen,
my sister.

38:15.996 --> 38:18.128
Uh, I've seen you
around the hospital.

38:18.163 --> 38:19.404
Have you talked
with her lately?

38:19.439 --> 38:20.603
DR.- I've tried.

38:20.638 --> 38:22.440
The nurses say
she won't take her meds.

38:22.475 --> 38:24.167
- Yeah,
she's funny that way.

38:24.202 --> 38:25.905
You must have seen
this kind of thing before.

38:25.940 --> 38:27.841
I mean, she's a psych patient...

38:27.876 --> 38:31.141
Chances are she's bound to have
a few eccentricities, right?

38:31.176 --> 38:32.780
DR.- Unless
she's willing to talk to me,

38:32.815 --> 38:34.749
there's absolutely
nothing I can do.

38:34.784 --> 38:36.817
- So that's it?
You're just giving up?

38:36.852 --> 38:38.522
DR.- No, not at all,

38:38.557 --> 38:43.186
but it's essential
that she take the first steps.

38:43.221 --> 38:45.925
- She's begging for help
but she wants to assert

38:45.960 --> 38:48.961
one tiny vestige of individual
power over her life.

38:48.996 --> 38:50.963
Where's the harm in that?

38:50.998 --> 38:52.635
DR.- There isn't,

38:52.670 --> 38:54.571
but it's a much
more complex dynamic

38:54.606 --> 38:57.904
than you might have learned
about in first-year psych.

38:57.939 --> 38:59.268
- She...

38:59.303 --> 39:01.303
she's obviously in pain.

39:01.338 --> 39:03.877
When do you apply all of your
training and your compassion

39:03.912 --> 39:05.142
to trying to fix her?

39:05.177 --> 39:07.210
Like, if you can't help her,
then who can?

39:07.245 --> 39:08.552
DR.- You're not
the first family member

39:08.587 --> 39:10.686
to take out their
frustrations on me.

39:10.721 --> 39:12.424
I'm sorry.

39:16.320 --> 39:18.320
- Sorry.

39:20.324 --> 39:21.224
Sorry.

39:26.935 --> 39:31.135
♪

39:31.170 --> 39:35.205
♪

39:35.240 --> 39:39.110
♪

39:39.145 --> 39:43.378
♪

39:43.413 --> 39:47.316
♪

39:47.351 --> 39:52.222
♪

39:52.257 --> 39:56.160
♪

39:56.195 --> 39:59.801
♪

39:59.836 --> 40:02.430
♪

40:04.874 --> 40:07.270
- Hello, Elfrieda.

40:07.305 --> 40:09.338
The community heard
that you were in the hospital

40:09.373 --> 40:11.714
and suffering deeply.

40:11.749 --> 40:13.749
Well, I'm here to let you know

40:13.784 --> 40:16.015
that when you
give yourself to God,

40:16.050 --> 40:18.182
you don't feel pain anymore.

40:18.217 --> 40:20.789
♪

40:20.824 --> 40:24.254
♪

40:24.289 --> 40:28.896
Shall we pray
together for your soul?

40:28.931 --> 40:31.129
- What?
Holy fuck!

40:31.164 --> 40:33.230
I hope she told him
to go fuck himself.

40:33.265 --> 40:34.737
Also, where were the nurses?

40:34.772 --> 40:36.772
I'm not allowed to
talk on my cell phone,

40:36.807 --> 40:38.774
but they're just
letting strangers into

40:38.809 --> 40:40.776
the rooms of their patients?
What is wrong with them?

40:40.811 --> 40:42.272
- Ugh.
I wanted to kill him.

40:42.307 --> 40:44.615
- I hope she--
seriously, she should have

40:44.650 --> 40:46.243
strangled him
with her underwear.

40:46.278 --> 40:49.444
- They don't let patients
on suicide watch wear underwear.

40:49.479 --> 40:51.116
- Really?
- No, they don't.

40:51.151 --> 40:54.922
- Huh.

40:54.957 --> 40:56.660
- What are days for?

40:56.695 --> 40:58.321
- What's that
supposed to mean?

40:58.356 --> 41:00.455
- Days are where we live.

41:00.490 --> 41:01.995
- What?
What was she talking about?

41:02.030 --> 41:04.602
- That was
the poem she was reciting,

41:04.637 --> 41:08.397
Philip Larkin's "Days."

41:08.432 --> 41:11.906
- They come, they wake us,
time and time over.

41:11.941 --> 41:14.139
- They are
to be happy in.

41:14.174 --> 41:16.944
- Where can we live
but days?

41:16.979 --> 41:18.374
- I like that.
- That's the setup.

41:18.409 --> 41:20.277
There's a second verse.

41:20.312 --> 41:25.315
- Ah, solving that question

41:25.350 --> 41:28.857
brings the priest
and the doctor

41:28.892 --> 41:31.926
and their long coats

41:31.961 --> 41:35.534
running over the fields.

41:38.495 --> 41:42.673
- He left pretty quickly
after the clothes came off.

41:42.708 --> 41:46.138
That's fucking amazing.

41:46.173 --> 41:48.844
I mean, a striptease
to a Larkin poem?

41:48.879 --> 41:50.582
It's brilliant.

41:53.180 --> 41:54.146
Maybe it's a sign.

41:56.381 --> 41:58.051
A turning point.

41:58.086 --> 42:01.956
That she gives enough of a fuck
to piss someone off, you know?

42:01.991 --> 42:04.189
Or to get out of bed.

42:04.224 --> 42:05.355
- Maybe.

42:14.498 --> 42:17.169
- Do you regret
having kids?

42:17.204 --> 42:20.678
- What?
Why would you say that?

42:20.713 --> 42:22.537
- I don't know.
Just wondering.

42:26.312 --> 42:28.686
- Am I such a terrible
mother that I give you

42:28.721 --> 42:31.249
the impression that your birth
was a negative event in my life?

42:31.284 --> 42:34.219
- No, not really.

42:34.254 --> 42:39.224
I just wonder, and don't
take this the wrong way,

42:39.259 --> 42:41.523
you seem unhappy.

42:47.773 --> 42:49.806
- Do I seem unhappy to you?

42:53.779 --> 42:57.143
- Not any more
than the rest of us.

42:57.178 --> 43:00.883
- In comparison to me,
you and Mom just seem so...

43:00.918 --> 43:04.414
buoyant.

43:04.449 --> 43:05.888
Like people who
have a great capacity

43:05.923 --> 43:08.022
for dealing with things,

43:08.057 --> 43:11.223
for keeping
their heads above water.

43:15.064 --> 43:19.264
- When your father died,
he had $76 on him.

43:19.299 --> 43:22.300
Do you remember what
your mom did with that money?

43:22.335 --> 43:23.939
- No.

43:23.974 --> 43:27.712
- She used it
to get Thai takeout.

43:27.747 --> 43:29.747
I mean, what's the alternative?

43:29.782 --> 43:31.947
Keep the money and hope it will

43:31.982 --> 43:36.149
eventually reveal
some sort of answer?

43:36.184 --> 43:38.448
- The food wasn't that good,
if I remember correctly.

43:38.483 --> 43:41.220
- Or maybe it was
the best takeout ever,

43:41.255 --> 43:43.695
but to you...

43:43.730 --> 43:45.620
it still tasted like shit.

43:56.303 --> 43:58.435
- What's this?

43:58.470 --> 44:00.503
- It came in the mail
today for Elf.

44:02.848 --> 44:06.278
- It's very...
specific and thorough

44:06.313 --> 44:08.511
in explaining all the ways
to commit suicide.

44:08.546 --> 44:10.645
- She was able to order
this from her hospital bed?

44:10.680 --> 44:13.450
- No, before
she tried to kill herself.

44:13.485 --> 44:15.221
It was on back order.

44:15.256 --> 44:16.827
- You should throw it away.
- I can't.

44:16.862 --> 44:18.455
That's an invasion
of her privacy.

44:18.490 --> 44:20.325
You can't just throw out
someone else's mail.

44:20.360 --> 44:22.129
- Well, then hide it
in the back of a closet

44:22.164 --> 44:26.034
until she stops being suicidal.

44:26.069 --> 44:28.201
So, I was thinking.

44:28.236 --> 44:31.666
What if we did
something extreme with Elf?

44:31.701 --> 44:35.703
Like, we parachute her into
North Korea or Mogadishu,

44:35.738 --> 44:38.046
or, like, Baffin Island,

44:38.081 --> 44:40.180
and she's forced to survive
on her own like never before.

44:40.215 --> 44:42.512
Maybe it would jolt her
into a new notion

44:42.547 --> 44:43.711
of what it means to be alive.

44:43.746 --> 44:46.186
Like, her adrenal gland
would kickstart

44:46.221 --> 44:48.716
a new life strategy
and then she'll realize

44:48.751 --> 44:51.862
that she doesn't
actually want to die.

44:51.897 --> 44:55.261
- Are you fucking serious?

44:55.296 --> 44:56.592
- I realize
that the plan has

44:56.627 --> 44:58.528
a number of
logistical challenges.

44:58.563 --> 45:00.662
- Like a child soldier
killing her?

45:00.697 --> 45:02.873
Or the fact that
she doesn't parachute?

45:02.908 --> 45:05.172
- So, what?

45:05.207 --> 45:08.670
We wait, in the hope
that miraculously,

45:08.705 --> 45:10.507
pragmatism, psychiatry,

45:10.542 --> 45:13.015
and pharmaceuticals
will save the day?

45:13.050 --> 45:15.281
- Doesn't she seem
to be getting better?

45:15.316 --> 45:16.678
- Based on what evidence?

45:16.713 --> 45:19.252
- She was asking
about Claudio, the tour.

45:19.287 --> 45:21.617
- She asked about the tour?
- Yes.

45:21.652 --> 45:23.960
- Without prompting?
- Yes.

45:38.471 --> 45:39.404
- Hello?

45:43.212 --> 45:45.377
- YVR.

45:45.412 --> 45:49.612
Your initials are the same
as the Vancouver Airport code.

45:49.647 --> 45:51.086
I thought it was you
when you called.

45:51.121 --> 45:53.616
I don't know too
many other Yolis.

45:53.651 --> 45:55.926
- It's good
to see you again.

45:55.961 --> 45:59.292
So, how's my mother's car?

45:59.327 --> 46:03.197
- Yeah, that's a different
story altogether, isn't it?

46:03.232 --> 46:05.595
- It was a snapshot,

46:05.630 --> 46:07.300
and then I realized
that in the last 15 years,

46:07.335 --> 46:09.599
I've morphed into
all these other selves.

46:09.634 --> 46:12.074
A soon-to-be-divorced woman
who left her husband

46:12.109 --> 46:15.704
for reasons that seemed
valid at the time.

46:15.739 --> 46:18.707
A grotesquely
undiscerning lover.

46:18.742 --> 46:21.380
A mother who's afraid her
parenting will be the cause

46:21.415 --> 46:24.482
of her child's
unhappiness, and...

46:24.517 --> 46:27.584
sitting in his truck,

46:27.619 --> 46:29.861
we were so... old.

46:32.360 --> 46:34.261
- When I saw you,
all I could think about

46:34.296 --> 46:38.100
was our younger selves,
like how different I was at 21,

46:38.135 --> 46:41.906
how full of optimism,
expectations.

46:41.941 --> 46:43.666
And now, um...

46:43.701 --> 46:45.239
- I know what you mean.

46:45.274 --> 46:49.639
I was punching way above my
weight even going to university.

46:49.674 --> 46:52.015
I mean,
never mind creative writing.

46:52.050 --> 46:53.676
Oh my god.

46:53.711 --> 46:56.921
Yeah, I never graduated.

46:56.956 --> 46:58.450
- Any regrets?
- No.

46:58.485 --> 47:02.619
I mean, not about that.

47:02.654 --> 47:06.326
Did you know I had a nickname?

47:06.361 --> 47:07.998
- No,
I don't remember that.

47:08.033 --> 47:09.395
YOLI V.O.: Of course I knew.

47:09.430 --> 47:11.133
I was the one
who gave it to him.

47:11.168 --> 47:12.937
- Yeah, Sad Jason.

47:12.972 --> 47:15.137
- Really?
Why?

47:15.172 --> 47:18.173
- The only reason
I even enrolled in university

47:18.208 --> 47:21.506
in the first place
is because I had this girlfriend

47:21.541 --> 47:24.113
in high school,
and I was very in love,

47:24.148 --> 47:26.511
and she broke up with me,

47:26.546 --> 47:30.548
and I just was wandering around,
you know, in a daze,

47:30.583 --> 47:35.058
couldn't concentrate,
so I became Sad Jason.

47:35.093 --> 47:40.360
I truly was the Eeyore
of undergraduates.

47:43.068 --> 47:46.729
- Yeah, well,
aside from the alliteration,

47:46.764 --> 47:51.404
there's irony
as history repeats itself.

47:51.439 --> 47:54.605
I am in the middle
of a divorce.

47:54.640 --> 47:56.838
- You okay?
- Yeah.

47:56.873 --> 47:59.115
God, at least
we don't have kids.

47:59.150 --> 48:01.513
That would be awful.
- Yeah.

48:03.781 --> 48:04.714
Yeah.

48:09.127 --> 48:10.588
Have you ever
been to Rotterdam?

48:13.791 --> 48:15.758
- ...Yeah!

48:15.793 --> 48:18.035
Good times.
You?

48:18.070 --> 48:21.533
- No.

48:21.568 --> 48:23.898
I feel like I'm being weird.
I'm sorry.

48:23.933 --> 48:26.868
- That's
how I remember you.

48:26.903 --> 48:30.839
- It's been
really nice to talk.

48:30.874 --> 48:33.281
- Hmm.

48:33.316 --> 48:36.581
YOLI V.O.: And so,
I imagined we were...

48:36.616 --> 48:40.915
young and horny and very happy.

48:40.950 --> 48:42.620
Afterwards,
he wanted to know why

48:42.655 --> 48:45.128
I asked him about Rotterdam,
so I told him

48:45.163 --> 48:48.428
the premise of the book
I'm trying to write.

48:48.463 --> 48:51.200
- There's this harbourmaster
who ends up on a ship

48:51.235 --> 48:52.465
that he kind of shouldn't be on,

48:52.500 --> 48:53.796
like he should
have gotten off it,

48:53.831 --> 48:55.567
but there's a storm,

48:55.602 --> 48:57.767
and so he can't get onto
his little boat to go back home,

48:57.802 --> 48:59.637
so he's stuck on this ship
going to Rotterdam,

48:59.672 --> 49:01.870
and then he misses
this meeting.

49:01.905 --> 49:05.247
Like, everything
goes wrong for him.

49:05.282 --> 49:07.513
- Wouldn't he be able
to explain to her

49:07.548 --> 49:10.615
he's trapped
with technology now?

49:10.650 --> 49:11.946
Text or whatever.

49:11.981 --> 49:15.092
- I know,
but for some reason he can't.

49:15.127 --> 49:16.720
I'm just-- I'm having
structural problems.

49:16.755 --> 49:19.096
- Your structure
is amazing.

49:19.131 --> 49:20.361
ELF V.O.: Please tell me
he didn't say,

49:20.396 --> 49:21.956
"Your structure is amazing."

49:21.991 --> 49:23.760
- Those were
his exact words.

49:23.795 --> 49:27.071
- Did you just
throw up all over him?

49:27.106 --> 49:28.501
- Yours too.

49:28.536 --> 49:30.833
- Oh, god!

49:30.868 --> 49:33.000
- I just think
the thing is about your book,

49:33.035 --> 49:35.640
it should move really fast.

49:35.675 --> 49:37.312
You know,
like pedal to the metal,

49:37.347 --> 49:39.644
so it doesn't get boring.
- Mm-hm.

49:39.679 --> 49:43.351
- Plus,
writing is so hard, right?

49:43.386 --> 49:46.453
You just want to get in there
and get the job done

49:46.488 --> 49:51.194
and get out,
like cleaning septic tanks.

49:51.229 --> 49:53.163
- Definitely.

49:53.198 --> 49:55.528
YOLI V.O.: Elf,
he compared writing

49:55.563 --> 49:57.695
to cleaning septic tanks.

49:57.730 --> 49:58.993
- Yeah.

49:59.028 --> 50:00.995
YOLI V.O.: The more
I thought about it,

50:01.030 --> 50:03.338
the more the analogy
didn't seem so shitty.

50:03.373 --> 50:05.703
ELF V.O.: Oh, come on,
you go with the easiest

50:05.738 --> 50:08.145
and most obvious pun
and you call yourself a writer?

50:08.180 --> 50:10.345
- Stop it.
Stop it!

50:15.913 --> 50:19.486
- As I brought my fingers
to my nose to check

50:19.521 --> 50:23.358
if I reeked of motor oil or sex,

50:23.393 --> 50:27.659
I felt so ashamed.

50:27.694 --> 50:31.058
- Shame is so unnecessary.

50:31.093 --> 50:33.368
- Maybe.
Maybe not.

50:35.768 --> 50:40.705
Shame motivates us to say we're
sorry and to seek forgiveness.

50:40.740 --> 50:42.476
It also motivates
some of us to write books

50:42.511 --> 50:45.347
as a futile attempt
at atonement.

50:45.382 --> 50:47.184
Shame helps
to fuck up relationships,

50:47.219 --> 50:50.385
and we all know fucked up
relationships are the lifeblood

50:50.420 --> 50:54.356
of books and movies and theatre.

50:54.391 --> 50:58.426
Get rid of shame
and you can kiss art goodbye.

50:58.461 --> 51:01.660
But I long for a life
without shame.

51:04.236 --> 51:06.104
- You look so defeated.

51:09.571 --> 51:11.868
- Tell me, Elf,
how should I look?

51:13.575 --> 51:16.213
- Well,
it was just an observation.

51:16.248 --> 51:18.413
- Hmm,
it didn't sound like one.

51:21.880 --> 51:22.780
- Okay.

51:26.324 --> 51:29.556
Yoli...

51:29.591 --> 51:31.690
You gotta keep
your shit together.

51:31.725 --> 51:34.396
Especially for Mom.

51:34.431 --> 51:38.433
- Are you
fucking kidding me?

51:38.468 --> 51:40.336
Oh my god.

51:40.371 --> 51:42.965
Oh my god, look at you.

51:46.476 --> 51:49.576
- I don't want
to do this right now.

51:49.611 --> 51:51.413
- Has it occurred to you
that I'm the one

51:51.448 --> 51:52.744
who's colossally fucked up?

51:52.779 --> 51:55.142
That my entire life
is embarrassing?

51:55.177 --> 51:57.188
The having a kid at 18,
the divorce,

51:57.223 --> 51:58.783
the pathetic affairs,
the mediocre novels,

51:58.818 --> 52:01.258
fucking all of it
is a clusterfuck--

52:01.293 --> 52:04.151
and even worse, a cliché!
- Okay.

52:04.186 --> 52:06.593
- Has it occurred to you
that I also lost my father

52:06.628 --> 52:09.233
to suicide and I'm having
a hard time getting over it?

52:09.268 --> 52:11.862
That I also am struggling
to find meaning in my pathetic,

52:11.897 --> 52:14.964
stupid life and that I also
think that this whole thing

52:14.999 --> 52:16.966
is a ridiculous farce and
the only intelligent response

52:17.001 --> 52:18.506
would be to kill myself?
But I pull back

52:18.541 --> 52:20.442
from that conclusion
because it creates

52:20.477 --> 52:22.378
a certain onus
that is unpalatable,

52:22.413 --> 52:24.644
like your fucking
Virginia Woolf.

52:24.679 --> 52:26.514
You have...

52:26.549 --> 52:30.177
you have an amazing partner
who loves you

52:30.212 --> 52:32.322
and a career that
the whole world respects

52:32.357 --> 52:33.983
and gives you shitloads
of money for,

52:34.018 --> 52:36.524
a career that you could leave at
any moment and just be labelled

52:36.559 --> 52:38.185
"mysterious" or "eccentric,"
and go live in Paris

52:38.220 --> 52:39.824
in the fucking Marais
or whatever that--

52:39.859 --> 52:41.826
that fucking arrond, arrondis--
- It's called the arrond--

52:41.861 --> 52:43.157
- Don't you
fucking correct me

52:43.192 --> 52:44.664
with your superior
knowledge of French!

52:44.699 --> 52:46.468
You have a beautiful house
that magically cleans itself.

52:46.503 --> 52:48.800
- I have a cleaning lady,
Yoli.

52:48.835 --> 52:50.505
You have a low-grade
understanding of despair,

52:50.540 --> 52:51.803
by the way.

52:51.838 --> 52:54.872
- Can you not see
that I need your help?

52:54.907 --> 52:56.511
That maybe you're
here for a reason,

52:56.546 --> 52:58.315
which is to be a sister to me?!

52:58.350 --> 53:01.351
- You have had my help
all along, okay?

53:01.386 --> 53:03.584
I had to be perfect
so you could fuck up,

53:03.619 --> 53:05.883
and you were more than happy
to take on that role!

53:05.918 --> 53:08.754
Also, you know, one of us
had to show some fucking empathy

53:08.789 --> 53:10.888
towards Dad and his
acres of existential sadness.

53:10.923 --> 53:12.824
- Why?
- Because nobody else would!

53:12.859 --> 53:14.155
- That means we chose life.

53:14.190 --> 53:15.893
It doesn't mean we don't
or we didn't fucking care.

53:15.928 --> 53:17.895
- You don't
understand a fucking thing!

53:17.930 --> 53:19.226
- I do understand!

53:19.261 --> 53:21.063
Just be like the rest of us:

53:21.098 --> 53:23.439
get fat, start smoking,
play piano badly, whatever.

53:23.474 --> 53:26.002
Just know that you'll eventually
get what you want most in life.

53:26.037 --> 53:28.543
- What's that?
- Death.

53:28.578 --> 53:31.073
So why can't you wait
around and be patient

53:31.108 --> 53:32.712
like the rest of us?

53:32.747 --> 53:34.846
Hasn't Mom suffered enough?
- That is so...

53:34.881 --> 53:37.112
- You just love the fucking
perverse idea of an encore.

53:37.147 --> 53:39.147
- Shut up!
You shut up!

54:15.658 --> 54:17.790
- Can't we just talk?

54:19.563 --> 54:21.255
- About what?

54:24.326 --> 54:27.767
- Anything.

54:27.802 --> 54:29.439
- Sure.

54:29.474 --> 54:34.642
But you seem to want me
to follow some hidden script,

54:34.677 --> 54:37.172
and when I veer from it,

54:37.207 --> 54:39.548
because I don't know
what it is in the first place,

54:39.583 --> 54:44.146
you're like,
"No, don't talk."

54:44.181 --> 54:48.183
You don't want me to talk about
the past because it's painful,

54:48.218 --> 54:51.659
because there were good times.

54:51.694 --> 54:53.155
There's life,

54:53.190 --> 54:55.432
and maybe it'll persuade you
to change your mind.

54:55.467 --> 54:57.764
And you don't want me
to talk about the future

54:57.799 --> 55:00.437
because you don't see one.

55:00.472 --> 55:05.442
So, um...

55:05.477 --> 55:09.171
okay, I'll just talk
about this moment.

55:12.176 --> 55:15.683
I inhaled.

55:15.718 --> 55:19.181
I exhaled.

55:19.216 --> 55:22.217
I'm standing up.

55:22.252 --> 55:26.122
I'm walking over here.

55:26.157 --> 55:29.631
A second is passing,

55:29.666 --> 55:32.436
and another one...

55:32.471 --> 55:36.033
and another one.

55:36.068 --> 55:38.409
- Have you thought
any more about Switzerland?

55:44.406 --> 55:46.681
- Does Nic know?

55:46.716 --> 55:48.584
- He would never take me.

55:48.619 --> 55:50.850
It has to be you.

55:50.885 --> 55:52.951
- What about Mom?
Did you tell her?

55:52.986 --> 55:56.284
- Yoli, listen to me.

55:56.319 --> 56:00.387
Mom and Nic can't know.

56:00.422 --> 56:02.829
Nic still believes
in some kind of medicine

56:02.864 --> 56:05.568
that's gonna cure me.
And Mom...

56:05.603 --> 56:08.164
Mom believes in
I don't know what.

56:08.199 --> 56:10.034
God?

56:10.069 --> 56:12.608
Or odds.

56:12.643 --> 56:16.645
But she's never gonna give up.

56:16.680 --> 56:21.243
It has to be you.

56:21.278 --> 56:23.410
- So, what?
We just sneak off to Zurich,

56:23.445 --> 56:25.522
just the two of us?

56:25.557 --> 56:28.118
- Yeah, why not?

56:28.153 --> 56:30.494
- Because Nic
would notice in five minutes

56:30.529 --> 56:31.924
that you were gone.
He would...

56:31.959 --> 56:34.388
he would put it
together somehow,

56:34.423 --> 56:36.423
find a paper trail.
Then he'd hate me,

56:36.458 --> 56:37.864
and Mom would have
a heart attack.

56:37.899 --> 56:39.932
It's so ridiculous, Elf.

56:39.967 --> 56:41.571
It's so improbable.

56:41.606 --> 56:43.936
- If you love me, Yoli,
you would take me.

56:43.971 --> 56:45.234
- I do love you.

56:45.269 --> 56:49.172
I love you so--

56:49.207 --> 56:51.075
- These came for you.

56:51.110 --> 56:52.846
- Oh, okay.
Yeah.

56:52.881 --> 56:55.442
You can give those to me.

56:55.477 --> 56:57.246
Thank you.

57:33.856 --> 57:36.989
I have a piano inside of me.

57:40.830 --> 57:44.029
- What kind?

57:44.064 --> 57:46.328
- An old Heintzman.

57:46.363 --> 57:48.770
♪

57:48.805 --> 57:52.939
- But it's completely
hollowed out and made of glass.

57:52.974 --> 57:54.941
♪

57:54.976 --> 57:58.912
I can feel it squeezing
against my ribs.

58:03.545 --> 58:07.250
Sometimes I can
feel the hard edge

58:07.285 --> 58:09.186
pushing against my skin,

58:09.221 --> 58:11.991
and I'm terrified

58:12.026 --> 58:15.456
that it's gonna break through
and I'll bleed to death.

58:18.670 --> 58:21.572
When I hear bottles smash,
I think,

58:21.607 --> 58:24.608
"This is it.
This is it."

58:24.643 --> 58:28.843
♪

58:28.878 --> 58:31.846
♪

58:31.881 --> 58:35.476
♪

58:35.511 --> 58:37.082
When I wake up in the morning,

58:37.117 --> 58:42.021
I have moments of
excruciating hope.

58:42.056 --> 58:46.091
The sun has risen and I think,

58:46.126 --> 58:48.698
"Maybe today will be different."

58:53.034 --> 58:55.771
But the day always darkens.

58:59.601 --> 59:02.206
It never changes,

59:02.241 --> 59:04.571
and I'm certain
that the future will be

59:04.606 --> 59:07.981
an endless repetition of
the same disappointment.

59:12.416 --> 59:16.286
No matter how hard I try,
I can't see beyond it.

59:16.321 --> 59:19.630
♪

59:19.665 --> 59:23.161
♪

59:23.196 --> 59:27.935
♪

59:27.970 --> 59:30.938
Take me to Switzerland.

59:38.750 --> 59:41.410
I don't want to die alone.

59:41.445 --> 59:44.655
♪

59:44.690 --> 59:46.789
♪

59:46.824 --> 59:49.616
- I don't want
you to die at all.

59:52.456 --> 59:55.666
♪

59:55.701 --> 1:00:00.330
♪

1:00:00.365 --> 1:00:04.598
♪

1:00:04.633 --> 1:00:07.876
♪

1:00:07.911 --> 1:00:12.276
♪

1:00:12.311 --> 1:00:15.686
♪

1:00:15.721 --> 1:00:19.613
♪

1:00:19.648 --> 1:00:23.793
♪

1:00:23.828 --> 1:00:27.654
♪

1:00:27.689 --> 1:00:31.064
♪

1:00:31.099 --> 1:00:35.200
♪

1:00:35.235 --> 1:00:38.973
♪

1:00:39.008 --> 1:00:42.174
♪

1:00:42.209 --> 1:00:44.011
♪

1:00:55.717 --> 1:00:58.520
- Yoli, you promised
to send the divorce papers

1:00:58.555 --> 1:01:01.292
three days ago,
and they're still not here.

1:01:01.327 --> 1:01:04.295
What's the problem?

1:01:04.330 --> 1:01:06.429
- You're young,
you're in love.

1:01:06.464 --> 1:01:09.498
Irony is your
default mechanism.

1:01:09.533 --> 1:01:12.039
"Let's get matching tattoos!

1:01:12.074 --> 1:01:16.813
"Let us slay hypocrisy
with jokes and magic."

1:01:16.848 --> 1:01:18.848
- Till death do us part.

1:01:26.990 --> 1:01:28.286
- Hey, Mom.

1:01:28.321 --> 1:01:31.795
- Your aunt,
she fainted today.

1:01:33.755 --> 1:01:36.129
- What-- is--
is she alright?

1:01:36.164 --> 1:01:37.526
- Well, she broke her arm

1:01:37.561 --> 1:01:40.529
and they've admitted her
to a chief cardiology.

1:01:40.564 --> 1:01:43.004
- Cardiology for her arm?

1:01:43.039 --> 1:01:46.667
- No.
She's having chest pains.

1:01:46.702 --> 1:01:50.440
That's why she fainted.

1:01:50.475 --> 1:01:53.113
- Okay.

1:02:22.705 --> 1:02:26.278
- Whoa,
what's your problem?

1:02:27.886 --> 1:02:29.545
- Excuse me?

1:02:29.580 --> 1:02:31.283
- You're way
too close to my car.

1:02:31.318 --> 1:02:34.253
If you scratch it, I swear,
there'll be hell to pay.

1:02:34.288 --> 1:02:36.684
- Hell to pay?

1:02:36.719 --> 1:02:39.093
Did you really just say
there'd be hell to pay

1:02:39.128 --> 1:02:41.458
if I touch your fucking car?

1:02:41.493 --> 1:02:45.902
Can't you see that my car
isn't touching your fucking car?

1:02:45.937 --> 1:02:48.102
- Hey,
what's your fucking problem?

1:02:48.137 --> 1:02:50.632
- My problem?
My problem!

1:02:50.667 --> 1:02:52.139
Fuck you!

1:02:52.174 --> 1:02:53.602
My problem is that
I have to go upstairs

1:02:53.637 --> 1:02:55.472
and see if my sister
feels like living today

1:02:55.507 --> 1:02:57.540
or if they can fix my aunt's
literal broken heart.

1:02:57.575 --> 1:02:59.377
And in case you haven't noticed,
the parking spots

1:02:59.412 --> 1:03:01.280
in this hospital are
really fucking small!

1:03:01.315 --> 1:03:03.315
Hey, excuse me,
are you guys together?

1:03:03.350 --> 1:03:05.251
Is this shithead
the baby's father?

1:03:05.286 --> 1:03:08.089
Uh, just let me know one thing.

1:03:08.124 --> 1:03:09.783
Um, has he ever
cared about a human

1:03:09.818 --> 1:03:11.994
as much as he cares
about his fucking car?

1:03:12.029 --> 1:03:13.754
- Okay, okay, okay.

1:03:13.789 --> 1:03:15.789
- And God forbid
the biggest tragedy in his life

1:03:15.824 --> 1:03:17.461
is that his car may
get a fucking scratch!

1:03:17.496 --> 1:03:18.660
What the fuck are you doing?

1:03:18.695 --> 1:03:20.101
- I've got your
license plate number.

1:03:20.136 --> 1:03:21.465
Just don't hit the car.

1:03:21.500 --> 1:03:23.071
- Hey, don't you
fucking walk away from me!

1:03:23.106 --> 1:03:24.435
I am not finished yet!

1:03:24.470 --> 1:03:25.667
- Let's go, let's go.

1:03:25.702 --> 1:03:26.943
- Do you want
my fucking insurance?!

1:03:26.978 --> 1:03:28.307
You can have that!
Do you want my, uh,

1:03:28.342 --> 1:03:30.507
my tax returns
for the last ten years?!

1:03:30.542 --> 1:03:32.608
- You're crazy!
- Hey, fuck you!

1:03:32.643 --> 1:03:35.952
Hey, fuck you,
you stupid fuck!

1:03:35.987 --> 1:03:38.317
Fuck you!

1:03:38.352 --> 1:03:41.551
- Fuck!

1:03:41.586 --> 1:03:45.126
Fuck!

1:03:55.105 --> 1:03:56.533
- Everything okay?

1:03:56.568 --> 1:03:58.909
- Oh, yeah, just had
a little trouble parking.

1:04:06.017 --> 1:04:08.578
♪

1:04:08.613 --> 1:04:11.746
♪

1:04:11.781 --> 1:04:14.518
YOLI V.O.: My aunt was
being well taken care of.

1:04:14.553 --> 1:04:18.060
The nurse assured us that
her surgery would be routine.

1:04:18.095 --> 1:04:21.426
She looked us in the eye.
She laughed at our jokes.

1:04:21.461 --> 1:04:25.034
♪

1:04:25.069 --> 1:04:26.563
YOLI V.O.: If you have to end up
in the hospital,

1:04:26.598 --> 1:04:28.763
try to focus all your pain
in your heart

1:04:28.798 --> 1:04:31.898
rather than in your head.

1:04:31.933 --> 1:04:35.374
♪

1:04:35.409 --> 1:04:38.740
♪

1:04:38.775 --> 1:04:42.920
♪

1:04:46.750 --> 1:04:50.092
- Yolandi Von Riesen?

1:04:50.127 --> 1:04:52.391
- Oh!
Hello, Mrs. Funk.

1:04:52.426 --> 1:04:53.788
- I thought
you'd moved away.

1:04:53.823 --> 1:04:56.857
- I did, but I'm back.

1:04:56.892 --> 1:04:58.595
My aunt's in the hospital.

1:04:58.630 --> 1:04:59.860
- Tina Loewen?

1:04:59.895 --> 1:05:02.104
- Mm-hm.
She had an event.

1:05:02.139 --> 1:05:04.337
A coronary event.

1:05:04.372 --> 1:05:06.801
- My brother's
getting a valve replacement.

1:05:06.836 --> 1:05:08.242
Very straightforward.

1:05:08.277 --> 1:05:11.377
Doctors say he'll be
back to running in a week.

1:05:11.412 --> 1:05:13.280
Do you remember our son,
Gerhard?

1:05:13.315 --> 1:05:15.282
- Yeah, of course.
We were in the same grade.

1:05:15.317 --> 1:05:16.679
- Did you know
he's living in London now?

1:05:16.714 --> 1:05:18.615
- Ontario?
- No, no, no, England.

1:05:18.650 --> 1:05:20.386
Gives lectures
all over the world.

1:05:20.421 --> 1:05:22.091
Who would have guessed?

1:05:23.952 --> 1:05:25.721
- Not me!

1:05:25.756 --> 1:05:28.922
- Gerhard saw Elfrieda play
with the London Philharmonic.

1:05:28.957 --> 1:05:31.760
He said it was the most
amazing thing he ever heard.

1:05:31.795 --> 1:05:36.402
By the way, we were always very
supportive of her piano playing.

1:05:36.437 --> 1:05:37.964
What have you been up to?

1:05:37.999 --> 1:05:40.406
- Oh, just learning
how to be a good loser.

1:05:40.441 --> 1:05:41.737
- Yoli...

1:05:41.772 --> 1:05:42.771
I was looking for you.

1:05:42.806 --> 1:05:43.871
Hi, Marta.

1:05:43.906 --> 1:05:45.741
I got to speak to Elf's doctor.

1:05:45.776 --> 1:05:47.248
- Oh.
- Elfrieda?

1:05:47.283 --> 1:05:48.612
We were just talking about her.

1:05:48.647 --> 1:05:50.218
Don't tell me
she's in hospital too.

1:05:50.253 --> 1:05:53.584
- Yes, she cut her wrists
because she wanted to die.

1:05:55.225 --> 1:05:56.488
How's Gerhard?

1:05:56.523 --> 1:05:59.029
- Alright, Mom,
let's keep on moving.

1:05:59.064 --> 1:06:02.296
Really nice to see you,
Mrs. Funk.

1:06:02.331 --> 1:06:04.958
Say hi to Gerhard for me, okay?

1:06:22.186 --> 1:06:24.450
- Hi.
- Hi.

1:06:28.984 --> 1:06:31.457
- How's Aunt Tina?

1:06:31.492 --> 1:06:34.559
- Mm, you know, considering
she has a broken arm

1:06:34.594 --> 1:06:38.035
and they're about to open up
her heart, okay, I guess.

1:06:40.732 --> 1:06:43.073
- And Mom?

1:06:45.275 --> 1:06:47.275
- Stoic, as usual.

1:06:52.843 --> 1:06:55.008
Do you...

1:06:55.043 --> 1:06:58.220
do you remember
the letters you sent to me

1:06:58.255 --> 1:07:00.156
after I broke up
with that guy in Montreal

1:07:00.191 --> 1:07:03.126
and I was living alone?

1:07:03.161 --> 1:07:05.557
- No, I don't think so.

1:07:05.592 --> 1:07:08.164
- It was a quote
from Paul Valéry,

1:07:08.199 --> 1:07:10.694
and every day
a letter would arrive

1:07:10.729 --> 1:07:12.696
with a single word
written on it.

1:07:17.703 --> 1:07:20.275
"Breath."

1:07:20.310 --> 1:07:23.806
- "Dreams."

1:07:23.841 --> 1:07:27.073
- "Silence."

1:07:27.108 --> 1:07:30.351
- "Invincible calm."

1:07:30.386 --> 1:07:32.947
- "You will triumph."

1:07:42.090 --> 1:07:46.433
It took me months to figure out,
but when I did...

1:07:46.468 --> 1:07:48.105
wow.

1:07:51.836 --> 1:07:56.410
I don't believe I ever
wrote back to thank you.

1:07:56.445 --> 1:07:59.710
- I'm sure you did.
- Probably not.

1:07:59.745 --> 1:08:02.548
That would have been like me.

1:08:09.458 --> 1:08:12.525
I did some research
on Switzerland.

1:08:16.333 --> 1:08:19.169
♪

1:08:19.204 --> 1:08:21.930
♪

1:08:21.965 --> 1:08:24.537
- Thank you.

1:08:31.843 --> 1:08:34.976
But I think it's time I get
Switzerland out of my head.

1:08:35.011 --> 1:08:39.013
♪

