1:24:06.777 --> 1:24:10.614
- Elf had asked me
to go to the library for her.

1:24:10.649 --> 1:24:13.815
I said we should
have lunch first.

1:24:13.850 --> 1:24:17.049
And lunch was normal.

1:24:17.084 --> 1:24:19.018
And then I went to the library
to get the books

1:24:19.053 --> 1:24:21.460
and she said she was
gonna take a nap.

1:24:27.237 --> 1:24:30.997
- Libraries
and civilization.

1:24:31.032 --> 1:24:32.900
- What?

1:24:32.935 --> 1:24:35.001
- She believed
libraries were the bedrock

1:24:35.036 --> 1:24:37.146
of civilization.

1:24:37.181 --> 1:24:38.873
- She said
that when you borrow a book,

1:24:38.908 --> 1:24:41.645
you make a promise.

1:24:41.680 --> 1:24:46.353
- To return it.

1:24:46.388 --> 1:24:48.322
A promise to come back.

1:24:59.764 --> 1:25:01.929
- The funeral director
said that...

1:25:05.099 --> 1:25:07.737
because of the impact
of the train,

1:25:07.772 --> 1:25:10.575
we might just
want to see her hand.

1:25:16.418 --> 1:25:21.047
- I need
to see Elf's face.

1:25:21.082 --> 1:25:25.491
♪

1:25:25.526 --> 1:25:28.494
♪

1:25:28.529 --> 1:25:30.991
♪

1:25:31.026 --> 1:25:33.928
YOLI V.O.: So there she was,

1:25:33.963 --> 1:25:37.129
the hole in her head sewn up
like a homemade baseball.

1:25:37.164 --> 1:25:38.603
And that's when I thought,

1:25:38.638 --> 1:25:43.410
"Who's the jackass that
stitched up my sister's face?"

1:25:43.445 --> 1:25:47.172
And after a minute of staring
at her, hoping she would blink,

1:25:47.207 --> 1:25:52.012
open her eyes, and laugh
at the absurd spectacle,

1:25:52.047 --> 1:25:54.146
I changed my mind
and felt a powerful,

1:25:54.181 --> 1:25:56.984
oceanic wave of gratitude
towards the mortician

1:25:57.019 --> 1:25:59.657
who did his best
trying to restore

1:25:59.692 --> 1:26:02.231
my sister's beauty
for one last time.

1:26:14.377 --> 1:26:18.104
♪

1:26:18.139 --> 1:26:22.042
♪

1:26:22.077 --> 1:26:25.320
♪

1:26:25.355 --> 1:26:27.487
YOLI V.O.: So, Elf,
I finally checked out

1:26:27.522 --> 1:26:31.216
your beloved D.H. Lawrence.

1:26:31.251 --> 1:26:35.022
I remember your incredulity when
you found out I hadn't read it.

1:26:35.057 --> 1:26:38.531
God, you can be
a snob sometimes.

1:26:38.566 --> 1:26:40.995
Anyway, you were right
about the first paragraph

1:26:41.030 --> 1:26:45.230
of Lady Chatterley's Lover.

1:26:45.265 --> 1:26:47.705
"Ours is essentially
a tragic age,

1:26:47.740 --> 1:26:51.170
"so we refuse
to take it tragically.

1:26:51.205 --> 1:26:55.284
"The cataclysm has happened,
we are among the ruins,

1:26:55.319 --> 1:26:57.880
"we start to build up
new little habitats,

1:26:57.915 --> 1:27:01.620
"to have new little hopes.

1:27:01.655 --> 1:27:06.020
"It is rather hard work:

1:27:06.055 --> 1:27:09.958
"there is now no smooth road
into the future.

1:27:17.407 --> 1:27:22.003
"We've got to live, no matter
how many skies have fallen."

1:27:22.038 --> 1:27:25.204
- And no matter how much
shit we've buried ourselves in.

1:27:27.208 --> 1:27:30.451
♪

1:27:30.486 --> 1:27:32.915
♪

1:27:32.950 --> 1:27:34.422
LOTTIE V.O.: Do you remember
when your father

1:27:34.457 --> 1:27:37.953
tried to start
a library in town?

1:27:37.988 --> 1:27:40.659
ELF V.O.: The elders,
they kept saying no.

1:27:40.694 --> 1:27:42.496
LOTTIE V.O.: But he persisted.

1:27:42.531 --> 1:27:46.566
Completely out of character,
he refused to back down.

1:27:46.601 --> 1:27:49.866
Insisted it was
important to the community.

1:27:49.901 --> 1:27:53.606
So they told him, "If you
can get 400 signatures,"

1:27:53.641 --> 1:27:56.235
which was almost everyone
in the East Village,

1:27:56.270 --> 1:27:58.204
that they would consider it.

1:28:00.780 --> 1:28:02.450
- Hello?
- Oh, hello.

1:28:02.485 --> 1:28:04.485
Is Elfrieda Von Riesen there,
please?

1:28:04.520 --> 1:28:06.421
- How do you
spell the last name?

1:28:06.456 --> 1:28:11.085
- R-I-E-S-E-N.

1:28:11.120 --> 1:28:14.924
- I'm sorry, Miss Riesen
was released weeks ago.

1:28:14.959 --> 1:28:18.928
LOTTIE V.O.: Night after night
he went out.

1:28:18.963 --> 1:28:20.864
ELF V.O.: He was crazy.

1:28:20.899 --> 1:28:22.635
- Seriously?

1:28:22.670 --> 1:28:24.329
Are you certain some
mistake wasn't made?

1:28:24.364 --> 1:28:25.671
She was very sick.

1:28:25.706 --> 1:28:27.541
How can you be sure
she was ready to leave?

1:28:27.576 --> 1:28:29.378
- Who is this, please?

1:28:29.413 --> 1:28:32.612
♪

1:28:32.647 --> 1:28:36.418
♪

1:28:36.453 --> 1:28:38.310
- He was so proud.

1:28:38.345 --> 1:28:41.885
♪

1:28:41.920 --> 1:28:46.758
- He was so proud.

1:28:46.793 --> 1:28:50.025
Makes me want to cry even now
just thinking about it.

1:28:50.060 --> 1:28:53.765
♪

1:28:53.800 --> 1:28:55.569
♪

1:28:59.003 --> 1:29:02.840
- No offence, but this place
is kind of a shithole.

1:29:02.875 --> 1:29:06.008
- No offence, but the payout
from your life insurance policy

1:29:06.043 --> 1:29:10.210
doesn't really buy a whole lot
of house in Toronto these days.

1:29:10.245 --> 1:29:12.817
- Do you like
the monthly stipend of $2,000

1:29:12.852 --> 1:29:14.819
so you can finally
finish your novel?

1:29:14.854 --> 1:29:18.185
- A stipend?

1:29:18.220 --> 1:29:19.956
I couldn't believe
you actually used that word

1:29:19.991 --> 1:29:22.123
in your will.

1:29:22.158 --> 1:29:25.995
So Virginia Woolf.

1:29:26.030 --> 1:29:28.393
- "A woman must have money

1:29:28.428 --> 1:29:32.639
"and a room of her own
if she is to write fiction."

1:29:32.674 --> 1:29:36.038
So you finally got Mom
to move to Toronto?

1:29:36.073 --> 1:29:39.041
- It was time
to circle our wagons.

1:29:39.076 --> 1:29:41.582
We've lost half our men,
supplies are dwindling,

1:29:41.617 --> 1:29:44.816
and winter is coming.

1:29:44.851 --> 1:29:48.853
There was no debate,
no discussion.

1:29:48.888 --> 1:29:51.053
We three ladies
will live in this old,

1:29:51.088 --> 1:29:53.154
wretched house thanks to you.

1:29:58.634 --> 1:30:01.393
- How are you feeling?
- Okay, I guess.

1:30:01.428 --> 1:30:04.231
Some days are better
than others.

1:30:04.266 --> 1:30:06.431
- Man, I keep thinking
how hard it must be,

1:30:06.466 --> 1:30:08.301
especially because
she died by her own hand.

1:30:08.336 --> 1:30:10.435
- Okay...

1:30:10.470 --> 1:30:12.745
Can you please not say
"Died by her own hand"?

1:30:12.780 --> 1:30:14.208
- Sorry,
how should I say it?

1:30:14.243 --> 1:30:16.210
- She killed herself.

1:30:16.245 --> 1:30:17.409
If someone gets murdered,
do you say,

1:30:17.444 --> 1:30:20.753
"They died by another's hand"?

1:30:20.788 --> 1:30:23.855
This isn't
The Count of Monte Cristo.

1:30:23.890 --> 1:30:25.120
- I can't help but think

1:30:25.155 --> 1:30:27.320
it just seems like
such a selfish act.

1:30:27.355 --> 1:30:28.761
- Selfish?

1:30:28.796 --> 1:30:31.192
How can it be selfish?
If you...

1:30:31.227 --> 1:30:32.798
if you haven't felt
agony firsthand,

1:30:32.833 --> 1:30:36.296
you can't pass judgement.

1:30:36.331 --> 1:30:39.970
- Can I get
a refill, please?

1:30:40.005 --> 1:30:41.972
- Actually lately,
more and more,

1:30:42.007 --> 1:30:44.546
I've begun to measure a person's
character and integrity

1:30:44.581 --> 1:30:46.911
by their ability
to kill themselves.

1:30:46.946 --> 1:30:48.341
- This ought to be good.

1:30:48.376 --> 1:30:50.376
- Thank you.

1:30:50.411 --> 1:30:52.785
What the hell are
you talking about?

1:30:52.820 --> 1:30:54.248
- Vladimir Putin?
No way.

1:30:54.283 --> 1:30:56.525
Jeremy Irons?
Yeah.

1:30:56.560 --> 1:30:58.219
Donald Trump?

1:30:58.254 --> 1:31:02.058
Like, no question, not a chance.
That kind of thing.

1:31:02.093 --> 1:31:04.632
- And me?

1:31:04.667 --> 1:31:06.667
Do I have what it takes
to kill myself?

1:31:24.786 --> 1:31:26.654
- When I looked up
Final Exit on Amazon,

1:31:26.689 --> 1:31:29.756
I was shocked by how high
the user ratings were.

1:31:29.791 --> 1:31:31.692
There were a couple of
verified purchasers

1:31:31.727 --> 1:31:33.518
who left glowing reviews
despite the fact

1:31:33.553 --> 1:31:37.896
that it was found next to
the bodies of their loved ones.

1:31:41.836 --> 1:31:45.167
- I have to
ask you something.

1:31:45.202 --> 1:31:47.774
Why do you keep
calling the hospital?

1:31:50.108 --> 1:31:52.471
- I don't.

1:31:52.506 --> 1:31:54.341
What?

1:31:54.376 --> 1:31:57.179
- I tracked
your activities.

1:31:57.214 --> 1:31:59.445
I've seen the cell phone bills,
the calls,

1:31:59.480 --> 1:32:01.447
the empty wine bottles.

1:32:01.482 --> 1:32:04.153
- Looks like all your years
of reading mystery novels

1:32:04.188 --> 1:32:05.759
is finally paying off.

1:32:09.160 --> 1:32:12.029
- Are you trying to haunt
the hospital for letting her go?

1:32:19.104 --> 1:32:20.807
- That's
an interesting theory.

1:32:20.842 --> 1:32:22.809
Um...

1:32:22.844 --> 1:32:24.679
I don't know what I'm doing.

1:32:26.716 --> 1:32:28.584
- It has to stop.

1:32:38.123 --> 1:32:41.861
- They screwed up!

1:33:02.884 --> 1:33:04.246
- I'm sorry.

1:33:04.281 --> 1:33:06.050
- Mm-mm.

1:33:15.622 --> 1:33:19.228
You know,
we can all fight really hard,

1:33:19.263 --> 1:33:22.594
but we can also
acknowledge defeat,

1:33:22.629 --> 1:33:25.971
stop fighting,
and just call a spade a spade.

1:33:29.812 --> 1:33:34.210
- What do you do
when a spade isn't a spade?

1:33:34.245 --> 1:33:38.214
- Well, yeah, there
are things like that in life

1:33:38.249 --> 1:33:41.481
that aren't spades,
and we can just let them...

1:33:41.516 --> 1:33:44.924
stay that way.

1:33:44.959 --> 1:33:47.289
- I'm a writer.
It's very difficult

1:33:47.324 --> 1:33:51.194
for me to leave those
spades so undefined.

1:33:51.229 --> 1:33:53.130
- I realize that.

1:33:58.005 --> 1:34:02.007
The problem is
the pain of letting go

1:34:02.042 --> 1:34:05.670
of grief is...

1:34:05.705 --> 1:34:08.145
it's just as painful,

1:34:08.180 --> 1:34:11.786
even more painful
than the grief itself.

1:34:14.549 --> 1:34:17.418
We're meant to move on.

1:34:17.453 --> 1:34:21.730
♪

1:34:21.765 --> 1:34:24.491
♪

1:34:24.526 --> 1:34:28.264
♪

1:34:28.299 --> 1:34:32.972
♪

1:34:34.404 --> 1:34:38.208
♪

1:34:41.741 --> 1:34:43.312
- You know,
this surely has to constitute

1:34:43.347 --> 1:34:44.511
some sort of child abuse,

1:34:44.546 --> 1:34:47.052
making me watch you
sign the divorce papers!

1:34:47.087 --> 1:34:49.956
- Yeah, well, unfortunately
someone needs to bear witness

1:34:49.991 --> 1:34:53.454
to my failure, and who better
than the product of the union?

1:34:53.489 --> 1:34:55.225
- You know what?
That is an interesting theory.

1:34:55.260 --> 1:34:56.996
I will be sure to bring
that up with my therapist

1:34:57.031 --> 1:34:58.833
that I'm gonna need
for the rest of my life.

1:34:58.868 --> 1:35:00.659
- Sounds great, as long
as your father pays for it.

1:35:00.694 --> 1:35:01.561
- Mm.

1:35:09.978 --> 1:35:11.571
You okay?

1:35:15.313 --> 1:35:18.182
♪

1:35:18.217 --> 1:35:21.185
♪

1:35:21.220 --> 1:35:24.023
YOLI V.O.: I could sense
the book was coming to an end.

1:35:24.058 --> 1:35:27.323
The novel, but really a memoir
with enough red herrings

1:35:27.358 --> 1:35:31.426
that I could deny everything,
was approaching 130,000 words.

1:35:31.461 --> 1:35:34.330
I'd give my mother
the word count in the morning.

1:35:34.365 --> 1:35:36.596
My guess, she'd be disappointed
with the sorrow quotient

1:35:36.631 --> 1:35:39.335
my literary efforts
once again produced.

1:35:39.370 --> 1:35:41.568
There was no Rotterdam plot.

1:35:41.603 --> 1:35:43.438
I couldn't even rework
a tiny part of it

1:35:43.473 --> 1:35:45.341
as some sort of metaphor,

1:35:45.376 --> 1:35:47.442
though I tried.

1:35:47.477 --> 1:35:50.412
I was in that beautiful zone
where the words came easily

1:35:50.447 --> 1:35:53.283
and I was one of the productive
members of society,

1:35:53.318 --> 1:35:56.022
that it mattered,
that I was making a difference,

1:35:56.057 --> 1:35:58.684
that I had done my best.

